mits()` - commit walk loop (line 863):**\\n   ```go\\n   for count := 0; limit <= 0 || count < limit; count++ {\\n       if err := ctx.Err(); err != nil {\\n           return err  // Propagate cancellation\\n       }\\n       // ... walk first parent\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n3. **In `runExplainBranchWithFilter()` - after getting checkpoints (line 1150):**\\n   ```go\\n   if ctx.Err() != nil {\\n       return NewSilentError(ctx.Err())\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n**Status:** Interruptibility is properly handled at the top-level iteration loops.\\n\\n### The Performance Issue - NOT A SIGNAL PROBLEM\\n\\nThe \\\"hanging\\\" on repos with many checkpoints was **NOT caused by signal handling**, but by two severe algorithmic/I/O bottlenecks that made the command unresponsive to signals:\\n\\n#### **Problem 1: ReadLatestSessionContent Per Checkpoint (FIXED)**\\n- **Commit:** `eff1e18d` - Line 949-958 before fix\\n- **What it did:** For every checkpoint in the list view (236 checkpoints on this repo's main), called:\\n  - `store.ReadLatestSessionContent(ctx, cpID)` - reads multi-MB JSONL transcript blobs from git\\n  - `extractPromptsFromTranscript()` - parses entire blob as JSON just to get first prompt\\n- **Why it hung:** Go-git's pure-Go packfile reader is CPU-bound on large packfiles with no goroutine preemption points. With hundreds of checkpoints × hundreds of MB of JSON parsing, the loop becomes uninterruptible despite `ctx.Err()` checks\\n- **The fix:** Replaced with `strategy.ReadLatestSessionPromptFromCommittedTree()` which:\\n  - Reads only the tiny `prompt.txt` file directly from metadata branch tree\\n  - O(1) tree lookups instead of O(MB) blob reads\\n  - Result: list view completes in ~350ms instead of hanging\\n\\n#### **Problem 2: hasCodeChanges() Per Temporary Checkpoint (FIXED)**\\n- **Commit:** `eff1e18d` - Line 1093-1098\\n- **What it did:** For each temporary checkpoint, called `hasCodeChanges()` which performs:\\n  - `parentTree.Diff(commitTree)` - full tree diff via go-git\\n  - Resolves hundreds of tree/blob objects through packfile reader\\n- **Why it hung:** Same packfile reader bottleneck; each diff iteration has no preemption\\n- **The fix:** Replaced with `hasAnyChanges()` which:\\n  - Compares tree hashes only: `commit.TreeHash != parent.TreeHash`\\n  - O(1) operation, no packfile access\\n  - May include metadata-only checkpoints in list view (acceptable trade-off)\\n\\n### Context Propagation Through go-git\\n\\n**Important finding:** go-git's `Diff()`, `Tree()`, `File()`, and `Contents()` operations **do not accept context parameters**. They are synchronous blocking operations. However:\\n\\n1. These operations are **not called in the tight loop** anymore after the fix\\n2. The heavy-lifting operations that ARE called (`repo.Log()`, `iter.ForEach()`) do check `ctx.Err()` \\n3. Go-git's operations are fast enough now (tree hash comparison, prompt.txt reads) that they complete immediately and don't block signal handling\\n\\n### Refactoring Commit\\n\\n**Commit `8ea04275`** (after the performance fix):\\n- Moved `readPromptFromMetadataTree()` logic into `strategy.ReadLatestSessionPromptFromCommittedTree()` \\n- Better architecture: avoids hard-coding metadata branch layout in explain.go\\n- Added comprehensive tests for both the performance fix and context cancellation\\n\\n### Conclusion\\n\\n**The fix on this branch addresses the hanging problem CORRECTLY:**\\n\\n1. **Signal Handling:** Already properly configured (not the issue)\\n2. **Context Cancellation:** Already checked at iteration boundaries (not sufficient alone)\\n3. **Root Cause:** Algorithmic complexity - O(n×m) JSON parsing and tree diffs made the command CPU-bound for minutes\\n4. **Solution:** Replaced with O(n) light operations using fast tree hash comparisons\\n5. **Interruptibility:** Now immediately responsive to SIGINT/SIGTERM because:\\n   - Operations are fast (complete in <350ms)\\n   - Context checks happen in main loops\\n   - No long-running I/O operations in tight loops\\n\\nThe fix is **not about fixing signal handling**, but about making the operations fast enough that context cancellation checks occur frequently enough and operations complete quickly.\\n\\n### Files Changed\\n- `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/explain-hang-performance/cmd/entire/cli/explain.go` - Added `hasAnyChanges()`, improved `convertTemporaryCheckpoint()` and `collectCheckpoint()`\\n- `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/explain-hang-performance/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go` - Added `ReadLatestSessionPromptFromCommittedTree()`\\n- `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/explain-hang-performance/cmd/entire/cli/explain_test.go` - Comprehensive test coverage\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: ac250360ff7270cff (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 54103\\ntool_uses: 26\\nduration_ms: 51400</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"5db67928-9916-4fe7-ac50-b843d8475453\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-27T23:13:09.124Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"I need to understand whether the `entire explain` command can be interrupted by signals (SIGINT, SIGTERM). Specifically:\\n\\n1. Look at the main entry point (`cmd/entire/main.go`) and `cmd/entire/cli/root.go` for signal handling setup\\n2. Check if there's any `signal.Notify` or context cancellation wired to signals\\n3. Look at how `getBranchCheckpoints` uses context - does it check `ctx.Err()` or `ctx.Done()` during iteration?\\n4. Look at go-git's `Diff()` method and `tree.File()` / `file.Contents()` - are these operations that check context or could they block indefinitely?\\n5. Look at `ReadLatestSessionContent` and whether it passes/checks context\\n6. Check if the `explain` command's `RunE` function sets up any signal handling or context with cancel\\n\\nThe concern is that when `entire explain` is running slow operations (like go-git tree diffs or reading large transcript blobs), SIGINT/SIGTERM cannot kill the pro