ommits` — checks `ctx.Err()` every iteration\\n- `getBranchCheckpoints` committed loop (`iter.ForEach`) — checks `ctx.Err()` every iteration\\n- `listCheckpointsForBranch` — checks `ctx.Err()` at entry and every iteration\\n- `ListTemporary` / `ListCommitted` — check `ctx.Err()` at entry\\n\\n**The remaining unchecked loops are trivially fast now:**\\n- `getReachableTemporaryCheckpoints` outer loop over `shadowBranches` — typically 1-3 branches\\n- Inner loop over `tempCheckpoints` calling `convertTemporaryCheckpoint` — each call is two O(1) hash comparisons + one tiny file read\\n- `collectCheckpoint` in the committed path — one tree lookup for `prompt.txt`\\n\\nAdding `ctx.Err()` checks to these would add maybe a nanosecond of overhead per iteration, so the overhead cost is negligible — but the practical benefit is also near zero. These loops complete in microseconds now. The only scenario where they'd block long enough to matter is if go-git's packfile reader itself is slow (e.g., a corrupt or extremely large packfile), and in that case the blocking happens *inside* the go-git call, not between iterations, so a `ctx.Err()` check wouldn't help anyway.\\n\\nThe real protection against uninterruptible hangs was eliminating the expensive operations (`Diff()`, `ReadLatestSessionContent`), which this branch already does. Adding more `ctx.Err()` calls would be defensive but wouldn't change observable behavior.\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":996,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":118463,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":996},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYZRa66FthB5oFcwecXKP\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"5a483a6b-5177-46a1-b698-1f9a15f64708\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-27T23:15:37.527Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"5a483a6b-5177-46a1-b698-1f9a15f64708\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"